CDs were fabricated via a hydrothermal approach, and its PL excitation and emission spectra are shown in Fig. 3
                     a. The emission spectrum exhibits asymmetric peaks, which can be fitted by a four-Gaussian function (dotted lines). It is well known that the most fascinating feature of CDs is their strong and tunable PL properties, which can be attributed to differently sized nanoparticles (the quantum effect) and/or different emissive traps on the CDs surface, or a mechanism currently unresolved [21,34,35]. According to the previous reports [36–39], it is concluded that the broad-band emissions are attributed to core and surface state emissions, as shown in Fig. 3b. The CDs in the TEM and HRTEM (Fig. 4
                     ) show a relatively uniform distribution, and the diameter of it is mainly in the range of 2.5–5.0 nm. In the HRTEM micrograph (inset of Fig. 4), the lattice planes with a lattice spacing of approximately 0.208 nm can be clearly identified, which maybe reflect the (102) diffraction planes of sp2 graphitic carbon [40].
